SIMPLE: frounce
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Frounce
<hw>Frounce</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Frounced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Frouncing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>frouncen</ets>, <ets>fronsen</ets>, to told, wrinkle, OF.
<ets>froncier</ets>, F. <ets>froncer</ets>, perh. fr. an assumed LL.
<ets>frontiare</ets> to wrinkle the forehead, L. <ets>frons</ets>
forehead. See <er>Front</er>, and cf. <er>Flounce</er> part of a
dress.]</ety> <def>To gather into or adorn with plaits, as a dress; to
form wrinkles in or upon; to curl or frizzle, as the hair.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not tricked and <qex>frounced</qex>, as she was wont.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frounce</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Frounce
<hw>Frounce</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To form wrinkles in the
forehead; to manifest displeasure; to frown.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Commons <qex>frounced</qex> and stormed.</q> <rj><qau>
Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frounce</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Frounce
<hw>Frounce</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A wrinkle, plait, or
curl; a flounce; -- also, a frown.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An affection in hawks, in which white spittle
gathers about the hawk's bill.</def> <rj><au>Booth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frounceless</ent>⟦br⟧
